<h3 headerid="21" name="text"><a id="institutional" name="institutional"></a>Institutional</h3>
<p class="content">The various institutional grants outlined below are only available to students during the fall and spring terms and are not available during the summer term. Funds are limited and once the budgeted funds have been committed, no additional awards will be made regardless of the situation.</p>
<h3 headerid="22" name="text"><strong>UIC Undergraduate Grant Program</strong></h3>
<p class="content">The University of Illinois Chicago (UIC) is committed to providing access to higher education and minimizing loan debt for all undergraduate students by optimizing the positive impact of university supported grants on student retention and graduation while controlling the campus-based financial aid budget. UIC has allocated a portion of its operating budget to provide Illinois residents who are Pell or MAP eligible with supplemental grant aid that will support them to degree completion while attending UIC.</p>
<p class="content">The UIC Opportunity Grant is awarded to the neediest UIC undergraduates as defined by their eligibility to receive both the Federal Pell Grant and MAP Award. The UIC Opportunity Grant in combination with the Federal Pell Grant, MAP Award and other federal/state/institutional gift assistance will fund direct costs defined as tuition, differentials and fees (mandatory fees charged of all students). The maximum UIC Opportunity Grant a student may receive is $3,700 annually ($1,850 per term). However, depending upon the budgeted funds available and number of students eligible, maximum awards will be reduced accordingly.</p>
<p class="content"><strong>IMPORTANT:</strong> If as a result of reduced funding of the MAP Program by ISAC, UIC will not cover any shortfall. The UIC Opportunity Grant students receive will be based upon the MAP program being fully funded as per the state statutes with a maximum award of $5,340.</p>
<h4>Eligibility for the UIC Opportunity Grant</h4>
<p>Students must be enrolled at UIC and must complete a Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) each academic year. All FAFSA applicants will be considered for the UIC Undergraduate Grant Program; no other financial aid application is necessary.</p>
<p>In order to qualify for the maximum grant aid, students must also meet the following eight criteria:</p>
<ul>
	<li>FAFSA on file by February 15 priority deadline</li>
	<li>Must be a U.S. citizen or permanent resident</li>
	<li>Must have demonstrated financial need each semester</li>
	<li>Must qualify to receive the Illinois Monetary Award Program (MAP) each semester</li>
	<li>Must qualify to receive the Federal Pell Grant each semester</li>
	<li>Must qualify for Illinois resident tuition</li>
	<li>Must enroll for at least 12 semester hours each semester</li>
	<li>Must maintain satisfactory academic progress each semester</li>
	<li>Must have not completed their degree requirements for graduation</li>
	<li>Must not have received more than eight paid semesters of UIC Grant funding if enrolled as a first-time student or four paid semesters of UIC Grand funding if enrolled as a transfer student.</li>
</ul>
<p>The UIC Opportunity Grant will support up to 8 paid semesters if enrolled as a first-time student or four paid semesters if enrolled as a transfer student.</p>
<h2 headerid="23" name="text"><a id="applyingforotherassistance" name="applyingforotherassistance"></a>Applying for Other Assistance</h2>
<h3 headerid="24" name="text">UIC Scholarships</h3>
<h4>Incoming and Transfer Students</h4>
<p>The same documents that a first-time freshman or transfer student submits for admission to UIC are reviewed by UIC admissions and the student's college of study for scholarship consideration. UIC Admissions departments determine recipients for scholarships such as the Aim High/Chancellor's Fellows Program and President's Award Program. Students selected as recipients are notified in writing and the information is provided on the applicable Award Letter. Please note that the Honors College has a separate admission procedure which includes consideration for scholarships.</p>
<h4>Continuing Students</h4>
<p>Continuing students may be automatically matched and/or apply to campus scholarship opportunities through the campus centralized scholarship portal, UIC SnAP (Scholarship and Awards Program). Students must complete and submit a General Application in UIC SnAP each academic year in order to have access to scholarship opportunities. <a href="https://uic.academicworks.com/users/sign_in" target="_blank">Students may access UIC SnAP online</a>.</p>
<h3 headerid="25" name="text">External Scholarships</h3>
<p>Many private scholarships are offered each year to college students by a variety of corporate, professional, trade, government, civic, religious, social, and fraternal organizations. Applying for such scholarships can be time consuming, so it is important to start as early as possible. A quick way to start a scholarship search is to utilize specialized scholarship search sites online.</p>
<p>Several for-profit companies through the United States offer similar computerized search services, often charging fees. The University of Illinois Chicago SFAS does not recommend these services and suggests students thoroughly investigate them before submitting any fees to them. SFAS also cautions against providing banking or credit card information in scholarship applications or acceptance agreements.</p>
<p>SFAS posts notifications received regarding external scholarships on the scholarship board in the SFAS office and distributes a scholarship e-newsletter. UIC students may request the e-newsletter by registering online.</p></div><!--end #textcontainer -->



